ion -- t13 The Validity of Authorship: Postwar British Metafiction from Muriel Spark to William Golding -- t14 “The unreckoned consequences of art”: Authorial Realism in Munro, Carver, Roth, and Moore -- t15 Authorship Horror: Stephen King’s Misery (1987) -- t16 The Tremor of Genre: Making and Unmaking Writers in Suspense Fiction -- t17 Economies of Authorship in Contemporary (Auto‐)Fiction: Between Expressivism and Institutionalism -- tConclusion -- tAppendix 1: An Incomplete List of Authorship Narratives, 1800 –2022 -- tAppendix 2: Quantitative Survey, 1800– 2022 -- tList of Illustrations and Tables -- tGlossary -- tAcknowledgements -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFictional novelists and other author characters have been a staple of novels and stories from the early nineteenth century onwards. What is it that attracts authors to representing their own kind in fiction? Author Fictions addresses this question from a theoretical and historical perspective. Narrative representations of literary authorship not only reflect the aesthetic convictions and social conditions of their actual authors or their time; they also take an active part in negotiating and shaping these conditions. The book unfolds the history of such ‘author fictions’ in European and North American texts since the early nineteenth century as a literary history of literary authorship, ranging from the Victorian bildungsroman to contemporary autofiction. It combines rhetorical and sociological approaches to answer the question how literature makes authors. Identifying ‘author fictions’ as narratives that address the fragile material conditions of literary creation in the actual and symbolic economies of production, Ingo Berensmeyer explores how these texts elaborate and manipulate concepts and models of authorship. This book will be relevant to English, American and comparative literary studies and to anyone interested in the topic of literary authorship.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAuthors in literature. 0aAuthorship in literature. 0aFictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aAuthorship in narrative studies.  aLiterary sociology.  aNovel since 1800.  aRhetorical poetics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z978311117578208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023z97831113182640 cEPUBz97831110561800 cprintz978311105615940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311105616640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111056166423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111056166/original  a978-3-11-117578-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1b2023  a978-3-11-131826-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131918-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2023